04317nam a22005775i 9780300213959DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002139597 a10.12987/97803002139592doi  a(DE-B1597)485651  a(OCoLC)904281369  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBF371b.D68124 2015eb 7aPSY0080002bisacsh04a153.1/252231 aDraaisma, Douwe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForgetting :bMyths, Perils and Compensations /cDouwe Draaisma. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForgetting: An Introduction -- tCHAPTER ONE: First Memories: Islands in the Stream of Forgetting -- tCHAPTER TWO: Why We Forget Dreams -- tCHAPTER THREE: In Memory of Henry M. -- tCHAPTER FOUR: The Man Who Forgot Faces -- tCHAPTER FIVE: A Slope, Followed By an Abyss -- tCHAPTER SIX: Your Colleague Has a Brilliant Idea - Yours -- tCHAPTER SEVEN: The Galileo of Neurology -- tCHAPTER EIGHT: On Repression -- tCHAPTER NINE: The Myth of Total Recall -- tCHAPTER TEN: The Memory of the Esterházys -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN: The Mirror That Never Forgets -- tCHAPTER TWELVE: The Second Death -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN: The Art of Forgetting -- tQuestions About Forgetting -- tNotes -- tIllustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his highly praised book The Nostalgia Factory, renowned memory scholar Douwe Draaisma explored the puzzling logic of memory in later life with humor and deep insight. In this compelling new book he turns to the "miracle" of forgetting. Far from being a defect that may indicate Alzheimer's or another form of dementia, Draaisma claims, forgetting is one of memory's crucial capacities. In fact, forgetting is essential.   Weaving together an engaging array of literary, historical, and scientific sources, the author considers forgetting from every angle. He pierces false clichés and asks important questions: Is a forgotten memory lost forever? What makes a colleague remember an idea but forget that it was yours? Draaisma explores "first memories" of young children, how experiences are translated into memory, the controversies over repression and "recovered" memories, and weird examples of memory dysfunction. He movingly examines the impact on personal memories when a hidden truth comes to light. In a persuasive conclusion the author advocates the undervalued practice of "the art of forgetting"-a set of techniques that assist in erasing memories, thereby preserving valuable relationships and encouraging personal contentment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCognitive psychology. 0aMemory. 0aRecollection (Psychology) 0aRecollection (Psychology). 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Cognitive Psychology & Cognition.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311053800708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300213959.jpg  a978-3-11-053800-7  YUP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles